In a meeting between President Obama and President Xi Jinping of China, the two leaders agreed to sign the Paris climate agreement on April 22 and work together to bring it into force as soon as possible. They also discussed phasing down hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) under the Montreal Protocol and finding a global market-based measure for addressing greenhouse gas emissions from international aviation. The leaders also committed to cooperation on nuclear security, development, public health, and addressing the threat of North Korea's nuclear weapons. They reaffirmed their commitments to human rights, cyber issues, and ensuring a level playing field for businesses. The President urged China to peacefully address maritime disputes with its neighbors and uphold freedom of navigation and overflight.